evolutions. Placing families at the center of the French Atlantic world, Palmer uses the concept of intimacy to illustrate how race, gender, and the law intersected to form a new worldview. Through analysis of personal, mercantile, and legal relationships, Intimate Bonds demonstrates that even in an era of intensifying racial stratification, slave owners and slaves, whites and people of color, men and women all adapted creatively to growing barriers, thus challenging the emerging paradigm of the nuclear family. This engagingly written history reveals that personal choices and family strategies shaped larger cultural and legal shifts in the meanings of race, slavery, family, patriarchy, and colonialism itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamilieszWest Indies, French. 0aRacially mixed familieszWest Indies, French. 0aSlaveryzWest Indies, French. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCaribbean Studies.  aLatin American Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229306740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293067.jpg  a978-3-11-066591-8  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DEGb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016